article.headline: Hawaii 73, Tulsa 71 (2OT)
article.story: TULSA, Okla. (AP) -- Logan Lee sank two free throws with 56 seconds left as Hawaii beat Tulsa 73-71 in a Western Athletic Conference game that went into double overtime on Saturday. Lee hit a 25-footer as the shot clock ran out with 2:13 to play in the second overtime stanza to give the Warriors (15-4, 7-2 WAC) a 70-67 lead. Tulsa regained the lead on two free throws by Jason Parker and a drive by Seneca Collins before Lee's free shots. Down 72-71, the Golden Hurricane had two chances to tie the game and take the lead but Jarius Glenn missed both free throws with 26.9 seconds remaining and Parker's pass to Collins was knocked away. After Michael Kuebler made a free throw for Hawaii with 18 seconds left in the game, both teams scrambled for the ball but officials ruled that Hawaii had possession and called a timeout with two seconds left. Anthony Price intercepted the inbounds pass for Tulsa (7-11, 3-6 WAC) and threw up a 30-footer, but it hit the rim as time expired. Julian Sensley had his sixth double-double of the year with 20 points and 13 rebounds and Phil Martin added 15 points and eight rebounds as Hawaii outrebounded Tulsa 50-39. Lee and Jeff Blackett had 11 points each, including two key baseline jumpers from Blackett in the first overtime to keep Hawaii alive. Parker had 26 points while Glenn had 15 points and 10 rebounds for Tulsa. The Golden Hurricane shot just 37.7 percent and made only three of 18 3-pointers. Hawaii shot 35.6 percent. Hawaii had the ball at the end of regulation and the first overtime, but desperation shots by Kuebler and Blackett weren't close to the mark.
